{
  "id": "animals",
  "order": 3,
  "title": {
    "en": "Animals",
    "uz": "Hayvonlar"
  },
  "icon": "🐫",
  "blurb": "From the loyal it to the desert tuya",
  "article": [
    {
      "heading": "No he, no she",
      "body": [
        "Uzbek has **no grammatical gender** — one word covers a male or female animal, and the pronoun **u** means \"he\", \"she\" and \"it\" all at once. So *it* is simply \"dog\", whether it is a he or a she.",
        "The general word for animal is **hayvon**; farm and pack animals together are **mol**."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "bu it",
          "english": "this dog"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "oq mushuk",
          "english": "a white cat"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Animals of the Silk Road",
      "body": [
        "Some animals carry real cultural weight. The **tuya** (camel) was the engine of the Silk Road caravans, and the **ot** (horse) is woven through Central Asian life, from games to feasts. Out on the steppe you will still meet flocks of **qo'y** (sheep) and **echki** (goats), watched over by a working **it**."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "tuya",
          "english": "camel — the ship of the desert"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "ot",
          "english": "horse"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
